Attica Middle School
September 4 at 10:05 AM ·

On August 31, 2020 the USDA issued a press release stating they are extending free meals until December 31, 2020 or until the funds appropriated by Congress are exhausted. These meals will be free to students enrolled at the Attica Central School District.

In the event the free emergency meal program ends, we will go back to a Free, Reduced and Full Pay status using meal applications which can be found on our website, therefore, it is imperative that the district has the application on file no later than September 30th, 2020, regardless of enrollment status (i.e., hybrid or 100% remote learning). If you have any questions, please contact Kris Wicks, Food Service Director at (585)591-0400, ext. 1195.

post_text:
Good afternoon!
The Attica FFA was recently selected as one of four local chapters to participate in a cheese donation through the Butterfly Foundation's "Say Cheese" program. We received over 450 pounds of cheese from Yancey's Fancy that was then distributed to our community through the Attica CSD lunch program and the Attica Food Pantry. We are so grateful for the work of Jeff Durkin and George Jarett of the Butterfly Foundation as well as Bob Kozlowski and Matt Lamb for making this project possible. As always, the staff at Attica CSD did an amazing job adding the cheese to the hundreds of school lunches that go out several times each week. The Attica FFA is excited that they were able to support NYS dairy producers and processors in this challenging time. Thank you to all who helped make this project a possibility!

For all High School and Middle School students, please remember that any work that was assigned by March 12 (third marking period) is due by May 18. After May 18, no work that was assigned prior to the school closure will be accepted. For students in any grade level, any work that has been assigned in packets during the closure is due by June 5, and can be turned in at the main office of the respective school building from 8:00 am to 3:00 pm Monday-Friday, or electronically directly to your teachers. You do not need to wait until June 5 to turn it in, but all work must be turned in by June 5.

Thank you.

post_text: March is ART IN OUR SCHOOLS month. Every year, the Arts Council for Wyoming County invites local High School teachers to select 10 works of art from their school to submit for the Annual County Wide Art Show. This year, Mrs. Ryan and Ms. Steves have selected 5 artworks from their respective classes to submit to the show. Artworks from Connor Nusstein, Justine Kurowski, Jaelyn Robbins, William Stegura, Hailey Frost, Vanessa Gorny, Ash Vogel (2 submissions), Allison Church, and Katie Alfiero will be featured in the show. The show opens this Friday, March 6th and runs through March 27th at the ACWC Gallery in Perry, NY. Go check it out!

post_text:
Attica Senior Emily Tait had a great performance at the Section V Indoor Track Championships this past weekend held at the RIT Gordon Field House.

Emily finished in second place in both the long and triple jumps.

In the long jump, she jumped 18'81/4"...only 1/2" off of first place. In the triple jump, Emily jumped 38'51/2" for second place.

Emily will now move on to represent Attica Central and Section V next weekend (Sat. March 7th) at the 2020 NYSPHSAA Indoor Track and Field Championships held at the Ocean Breeze Track and Field Athletic Complex in Staten Island New York. Way to go Emily!!!!

post_text: Attica's Donate Life Club toured the Connect Life headquarters in Williamsville NY. Connect Life is Western New York's only community blood center and federally designated organ, eye and tissue procurement agency where all blood donated stays here to be used locally for the eight counties of WNY. The students tour of the facilities consisted of speakers for the following departments: Call Center which is the first step of the organ donation process where the referral comes in, then the Family Services department which deals with meeting and educating the family during such a difficult time, then off to the Eye and Tissue Lab where eyes and tissue are analyzed for donation, and lastly the Blood Lab where all donated blood from the blood drives gets processed for use in hospitals here in Western New York

post_text:
Mrs. Girdlestone's Personal Finance class and a few of Mr. Heck's Economics students were able to attend yesterday's Junior Achievement Stock Market Challenge. Attica's portfolio was able to have a 41% return on their investments. AHS finished in first place where the students split a $2,000 scholarship, $50 Tops gift cards, and the coveted Wall Street Bull Trophy (see slide show).

There were 34 schools from six counties in WNY, for a total of 580 students, with 145 teams in attendance. Students simulated the stock market exchange through a 60 minute session, where each minute equals one day.

AHS will keep the trophy for one year. The trophy will be displayed in the high school main lobby. This was an incredible victory by our students and the entire community should be proud of their accomplishments!

post_text:
Michele Lin just completed her summer research program at the University of Rochester. ACS is so proud of Michele for being accepted into the program and estatic that she completed the program!

The Laboratory for Laser Energetics (LLE) at the University of Rochester holds an annual summer research program for Rochester-area high school students who have just completed their junior year. The eight-week program provides an exceptional opportunity for highly motivated students to experience scientific research in a realistic environment. Students who are accepted into the program are assigned to a research project and supervised by a staff scientist at the Laboratory. These projects form an integral part of the research program of the Laboratory and are related to the Laboratory's 60-beam OMEGA laser, one of the world's most powerful fusion lasers, and the OMEGA EP laser, completed in 2008

Hello everyone, I just wanted to inform you about how proud I am of our students during the American Welding Society (AWS) competition https://www.aws.org/ . Competing this weekend were Joe Streit and Blake Pariso. They both represented the school proudly with Blake taking home 3rd place and receiving 1000$ to any school he chooses!

- Andrew Geyer, Welding instructor at Genesee Valley Educational Partnership.
